ke the sci-fi horror Doomwatch (1970–72) and the horror documentary Requiem for a Village (1975) alongside filmmakers Ken Russell and Ben Wheatley.A series of engrossing chapters by established scholars and new writers argue for the uniqueness of folk horror from perspectives that include the fragmented national history of pagan heresies and Celtic cultures, of peasant lifestyles, folkloric rediscoveries and postcolonial decline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFolk horror filmszGreat BritainxHistory and criticism. 0aFolklore in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Horror.2bisacsh  aArthur Machen.  aBen Wheatley.  aBritish cinema.  aDoomwatch.  aGenre Studies.  aKen Russell.  aRequiem for a Village.  aThe Blood on Satan's Claw.  aThe Company of Wolves.  aThe Wicker Man.  aWitchfinder General.  aanti-landscape.  acult cinema.  afolk horror.  afolklore.  ahorror.  apaganism.  athe wyrd.  aunholy trinity.1 aBayman, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayman, Louis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarroll, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, K. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Kevin J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvans-Powell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodall, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeetley, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4ht